The Comprehensive Crisis in Lebanon
Beirut —— In retrospect, financial crises usually seem to have warning signs before they occur; however, they rarely clearly indicate the direction of history.
Lebanon's current situation is the same, as a foreseeable crisis has plunged the country into a state of high instability.
Since the end of Lebanon's long civil war (1975-1990), its economic and political systems have been supported by external borrowing, inevitably leading to a continuous rise in public debt.
At some point, inflows of foreign capital had to stop. This point arrived at the end of 2019, followed by a series of negative shocks.
This "sudden stop" of capital has brought about a severe triple crisis for the country.
The first issue is the balance of payments.
Lebanon's current-account deficit is as high as 25% of GDP, and its export base is too small to even cover the costs of essential imports.
The second issue is fiscal.
Lebanon's public debt now totals over 150% of GDP.
Government revenue is collapsing under the pressure of the economic recession, and the budget deficit has already become significant, reaching 10% of GDP in 2019 and continues to expand rapidly.
Most importantly, Lebanon is also experiencing a banking crisis.
Major banks, which were the main recipients of foreign capital inflows, have heavily invested in Lebanon's sovereign debt (averaging 50% of their investment portfolios), and are now basically insolvent.
Together, these crises have pushed Lebanon's economy into a deep abyss.
Companies eager to borrow and import have begun laying off workers or completely shutting down.
An economic recession could lead Lebanon into a depression.
The main source of capital supporting Lebanon's fragile political economy is not oil, but remittances from the diaspora, who are attracted by high interest rates and a fixed exchange rate tied to the dollar.
It is therefore no surprise that there are signs of "Dutch disease" everywhere: deposits have grown to over 400% of GDP, creating a wealth effect that has reduced the national savings rate to an implausible level — 3% of GDP.
Inequality is very high and is still rising.
Between 2000 and 2015, the real (inflation-adjusted) exchange rate appreciated by about 50%, greatly weakening tradable industries.
Lebanon has been losing educated young people due to the lack of export goods and services.
But more importantly, the large inflow of capital allowed sectarian elites to consolidate their positions through patronage rather than performance.
These elites extracted wealth from both the public and private sectors, establishing a bloated patronage regime.
Although this ensured political stability in this otherwise chaotic region, it failed to meet basic needs.
Even electricity supply is discontinuous and unreliable, while the broader macroeconomic challenges remain completely unresolved.
The financial crisis triggered a political uprising.
A popular revolutionary movement took to the streets, opposing sectarianism and demanding an end to corruption.
Nevertheless, so far, the country's regime has overwhelmingly favored the elite in its response to Lebanon's economic issues, indicating that this crisis may ultimately be "resolved" with the support of the poor and middle class, further entrenching sectarian politics.
For example, the state refused to introduce capital controls, allowing the main shareholders of each bank, including the politicians in power, to decide how to quantify cash withdrawals.
In practice, this allows elites to transfer capital abroad, while ordinary citizens find it difficult to access their deposits.
Furthermore, the central bank has lowered deposit rates but has not reduced the interest rate on public debt, thereby increasing bank profits.
Despite the continuous decline in international reserves, Lebanon continues to repay its foreign debt, which is mainly owed to domestic banks.
There are signs that it may begin selling state assets to elite-linked entities at fire-sale prices.
Meanwhile, the official exchange rate remains unchanged, while elites allow access to dollars at a low exchange rate, whereas ordinary citizens face the reality of the rapidly declining free-market exchange rate. Currently, the free-market exchange rate is discounted by 40%.
When the country begins printing Lebanese pounds to pay public sector wages, depreciation will accelerate.
In fact, the central bank has already been paying interest on dollar deposits in lira (dollar deposits account for more than 80% of all deposits), thereby creating conditions for eliminating public debt through inflation.
By shifting the cost of debt reduction onto depositors through "liralization" via depositor ownership, the banks' equity is basically spared.
If this scenario becomes reality, Lebanon's middle class will be significantly reduced due to the decline in real wages and pensions, as well as the liquidation of savings.
The immigration process of educated young people will accelerate, and even the economic interests of the immigrant community — on which this system depends — will be damaged.
If the sectarian system is to survive under these conditions, it will rule over a poor population that can be controlled by increasingly cheap shelters.
Ultimately, Lebanon will find itself in a situation similar to that of Venezuela.
By contrast, the establishment of a new republic driven by revolutionaries will take a completely different approach.
Revolutionaries want to improve Lebanon, not abandon it.
They believe it is performing far below its potential, and performance, elite management, and social justice should replace corruption, nepotism, and inequality.
They hope to establish a vibrant high-tech industry, make agriculture more environmentally sustainable, position the country as a cultural powerhouse, and create more synergies with the diaspora communities.
To achieve these goals, the reform movement hopes to seek an orderly reduction of public debt, which will be secured by bank capital, and to forcibly cut deposits of savers with over 1% of total deposits.
They support a moderate currency depreciation and a thorough improvement of the business environment to enhance export competitiveness.
They will seek deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the elimination of corrupt practices and increased spending on social programs and infrastructure.
With the support of the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the inevitable recession will be mitigated.
The current infighting over the composition of Lebanon's next cabinet is part of a larger struggle in the country's pursuit of a new political solution.
The financial crisis poses a lethal threat to the country; but it also represents an opportunity for political change.
Lebanon's future remains uncertain.
